\begin{verbatim}
AutoEMAMdofProblem(prob, dpi, method; modetype)
\end{verbatim}
Structure containing the input data for automatic experimental modal analysis using Mdof methods

\textbf{Fields}

\begin{itemize}
\item \texttt{prob::EMAProblem}: EMA problem containing FRF data and frequency vector


\item \texttt{order::Int}: Model order (number of poles to extract)


\item \texttt{dpi::Vector\{Int\}}: Driving point indices - default = [1, 1]

\begin{itemize}
\item \texttt{dpi[1]}: Driving point index on the measurement mesh


\item \texttt{dpi[2]}: Driving point index on the excitation mesh

\end{itemize}

\item \texttt{method::MdofModalExtraction}: Method to extract the poles

\begin{itemize}
\item \texttt{LSCE}: Least Squares Complex Exponential method


\item \texttt{LSCF}`: Least Squares Complex Frequency method (default)


\item \texttt{PLSCF}: Polyreference Least Squares Complex Frequency method

\end{itemize}

\item \texttt{modetype::Symbol}: Type of mode shapes to extract

\begin{itemize}
\item \texttt{:real}: Real mode shapes (default)


\item \texttt{:complex}: Complex mode shapes

\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

\begin{verbatim}
EMAMdofSolution(poles, ms, ci, res, lr, ur)
\end{verbatim}
Structure containing the solution of the automatic experimental modal analysis using Mdof methods

\textbf{Fields}

\begin{itemize}
\item \texttt{poles::Vector\{Complex\}}: Extracted poles


\item \texttt{ms::AbstractArray\{Real\}}: Mode shapes


\item \texttt{ci::Vector\{Complex\}}: Scaling constants for each mode


\item \texttt{res::AbstractArray\{Complex\}}: Residues for each mode


\item \texttt{lr::Matrix\{Complex\}}: Lower residual


\item \texttt{ur::Matrix\{Complex\}}: Upper residual

\end{itemize}

\begin{verbatim}
StabilizationAnalysis(prob, poles, modefn, mode_stabfn, mode_stabdr)
\end{verbatim}
Data structure summarizing the results of the stabilization analysis.

\textbf{Fields}

\begin{itemize}
\item \texttt{prob::MdofProblem}: EMA-MDOF problem containing FRF data and frequency vector


\item \texttt{frange::Vector\{Real\}}: Frequency range used for the stabilization analysis


\item \texttt{poles::Vector\{Vector\{Complex\}\}}: Vector of vectors containing extracted poles at each model order


\item \texttt{modefn::Matrix\{Real\}}: Matrix containing the natural frequencies (useful for plotting)


\item \texttt{mode\_stabfn::Matrix\{Bool\}}: Matrix indicating the stability of natural frequencies


\item \texttt{mode\_stabdr::Matrix\{Bool\}}: Matrix indicating the stability of damping ratios

\end{itemize}
\textbf{Note}

This structure is returned by the \texttt{stabilization} function after performing a stabilization diagram analysis and used by \texttt{stabilization\_plot} for visualization.

\begin{verbatim}
poles_extraction(prob, order, method; stabdiag, weighting)
\end{verbatim}
Extract complex poles from Frequency Response Function (FRF) data using the specified modal extraction method.

\textbf{Inputs}

\begin{itemize}
\item \texttt{prob::MdofProblem}: MDOF problem containing FRF data and frequency vector


\item \texttt{order::Int}: Model order (number of poles to extract)


\item \texttt{method::MdofModalExtraction}: Modal extraction method

\begin{itemize}
\item \texttt{LSCE}: Least Squares Complex Exponential method


\item \texttt{LSCF}: Least Squares Complex Frequency method (default)


\item \texttt{PLSCF}: Polyreference Least Squares Complex Frequency method

\end{itemize}

\item \texttt{stabdiag}: Boolean to indicate the function is used to build a stability diagram (default: false)


\item \texttt{weighting}: Boolean to indicate whether to apply weighting of the FRF (default: true)

\end{itemize}
\textbf{Output}

\begin{itemize}
\item \texttt{poles}: Vector of extracted complex poles

\end{itemize}
\textbf{Note}

The \texttt{weighting} parameter is only applicable for the LSCF and PLSCF methods.

\begin{verbatim}
stabilization(prob, max_order, method; weighting, stabcrit)
\end{verbatim}
Perform stabilization diagram analysis using the specified modal extraction method (LSCE, LSCF, or PLSCF).

\textbf{Inputs}

\begin{itemize}
\item \texttt{prob::MdofProblem}: EMA-MDOF problem containing FRF data and frequency vector


\item \texttt{max\_order::Int}: Maximum model order for the stabilization analysis


\item \texttt{alg::MdofModalExtraction}: Modal extraction algorithm to use

\begin{itemize}
\item \texttt{LSCE()}: Least Squares Complex Exponential method


\item \texttt{LSCF()}: Least Squares Complex Frequency method (default)


\item \texttt{PLSCF()}: Polyreference Least Squares Complex Frequency method

\end{itemize}

\item \texttt{frange}: Frequency range for analysis (default: [freq[1], freq[end]])


\item \texttt{weighting}: Boolean to indicate if the weighting based on the variance of each FRF is applied (default: true)


\item \texttt{stabcrit}: Vector containing the stability criteria for natural frequencies and damping ratios (default: [0.01, 0.05])

\end{itemize}
\textbf{Output}

\begin{itemize}
\item \texttt{sol::EMAMdofStabilization}: Data structure containing the results of the stabilization analysis

\end{itemize}

\begin{verbatim}
stabilization_plot(stab::StabilizationAnalysis, indicator)
\end{verbatim}
Plot stabilization diagram for EMA-MDOF pole stability analysis.

\textbf{Inputs}

\begin{itemize}
\item \texttt{stab}: EMA-MDOF stabilization data


\item \texttt{indicator}: Indicator to plot

\begin{itemize}
\item \texttt{:psif} : Power spectrum indicator function (default)


\item \texttt{:cmif} : Complex mode indicator function

\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\textbf{Output}

\begin{itemize}
\item \texttt{fig}: Figure

\end{itemize}

\begin{verbatim}
mode_residues(prob, poles)
\end{verbatim}
Compute residues of a frequency response function (FRF) given its poles.

\textbf{Inputs}

\begin{itemize}
\item \texttt{prob}: EMAMdofProblem containing FRF data and frequency vector


\item \texttt{poles}: Vector of complex poles

\end{itemize}
\textbf{Output}

\begin{itemize}
\item \texttt{res}: Residues corresponding to each pole

\end{itemize}

\begin{verbatim}
modeshape_extraction(prob, poles; dpi)
\end{verbatim}
Extract mode shapes using Sdof approximation

\textbf{Inputs}

\begin{itemize}
\item \texttt{prob::EMASdofProblem}: EMA-SDOF problem containing FRF data and frequency vector


\item \texttt{poles}: Vector of complex poles


\item \texttt{dpi}: Driving point indices - default = [1, 1]

\begin{itemize}
\item \texttt{dpi[1]}: Driving point index on the measurement mesh


\item \texttt{dpi[2]}: Driving point index on the excitation mesh

\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\textbf{Output}

\begin{itemize}
\item \texttt{ϕn}: Mode shapes

\end{itemize}
\textbf{Note}

\begin{itemize}
\item If the number of measurement points is less than the number of excitation points, the mode shapes are estimated at the excitation points (roving hammer test). Otherwise, the mode shapes are estimated at the measurement points (roving accelerometer test).


\item The \texttt{alg} argument is here for performing multiple dispatch but is not used in the function.

\end{itemize}
\begin{verbatim}
modeshape_extraction(residues, poles, alg; dpi, modetype)
\end{verbatim}
Extract mode shapes using MDOF approximation

\textbf{Inputs}

\begin{itemize}
\item \texttt{residues}: Residues matrix of size (np, nm, ne)


\item \texttt{poles}: Vector of complex poles


\item \texttt{alg}: Modal extraction algorithm


\item \texttt{dpi}: Driving point indices - default = [1, 1]

\begin{itemize}
\item \texttt{dpi[1]}: Driving point index on the measurement mesh


\item \texttt{dpi[2]}: Driving point index on the excitation mesh

\end{itemize}

\item \texttt{modetype}: Type of mode shape

\begin{itemize}
\item \texttt{:emac}: EMA - Complex mode shapes (default)


\item \texttt{:emar}: EMA - Real mode shapes


\item \texttt{:oma}: OMA

\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\textbf{Outputs}

\begin{itemize}
\item \texttt{ms}: Mode shapes matrix


\item \texttt{ci}: Scaling factors vector

\end{itemize}
\textbf{Note}

\begin{itemize}
\item \texttt{alg} parameter is currently included for multiple dispatch purposes.

\end{itemize}
\textbf{References} [1] M. Géradin and D. J. Rixen. "Mechanical Vibrations: Theory and Application to Structural Dynamics". 3rd. Edition, Wiley, 2015.

[2] C. Ranieri and G. Fabbrocino. "Operational Modal Analysis of Civil Engineering Structures: An Introduction and Guide for Applications". Springer, 2014.

\begin{verbatim}
solve(prob::AutoEMAMdofProblem)
\end{verbatim}
Solve automatically experimental modal analysis problem using Mdof methods

\textbf{Inputs}

\begin{itemize}
\item \texttt{prob}: Structure containing the input data for automatic experimental modal analysis using Mdof methods

\end{itemize}
\textbf{Outputs}

\begin{itemize}
\item \texttt{sol::EMAMdofSolution}: Structure containing the solution of the automatic experimental modal analysis using Mdof methods

\end{itemize}
